Statement Guidance.title: Statement Guidance field schema
Statement Guidance.description: Statement Guidance field schema generated by the CEDAR Template Editor 2.6.18

_ui._content:
Statement

Lineage information can be provided as 1) structured descriptions of process steps, processing, inputs and outputs or 2) a descriptive statement.

Detailed information about process steps with inputs, outputs, and processing are more useful for users that are trying to understand and reproduce results using the metadata or for those analyzing other data using the same or similar techniques. They are also useful for users trying to use software provided with the dataset(s).

In some situations, a descriptive statement is all that is available. In those cases, provide a statement that is sufficient to help a reader of the high-level metadata understand what was done.

Including a statement and detailed descriptions is most useful for a wide range of users and use cases.

Statement Guidance.schema:name: Statement Guidance

_ui._content:
Entering Organization Name and Identifier

Unambiguously identifying organizations requires a name and a persistent identifier. For organizations, the Research Organization Registry is a community-supported source of organizational identifiers. Check ROR to see if your organization has a ROR. If yes, enter the name of the organization and the ROR.

Note: ROR is generally limited to high-level organization names, i.e. Universities rather then Departments. Select the name closest to the organization you are naming.

_ui._content:
Related identifiers enable the connections that are critical to forming the PID Graph. They are used to connect resources of many kinds to the resource being described by these metadata.

These identifiers are usually complete URLS. For example a DOI would be https://doi.org/DOI. The identifiers do not have to be DOIs or other standard identifiers. If the type of the identifier is not universally identifiable, provide it along with the URI of the identifier scheme.
